# Figma-to-Code Workflow Conventions

## 1. Fluid Typography System (vw/rem)

The site uses a viewport-relative rem system:

```css
html {
  font-size: 1vw;
}
@media (max-width: 639px) {
  html {
    font-size: 4.266667vw;
  }
}
```

**Conversion formula:**
- PC design (1920px): `rem = figma_px / 19.2`
- If design is 1600px: `rem = figma_px / 16`
- If design is 1440px: `rem = figma_px / 14.4`
- General: `rem = figma_px / (design_width / 100)`
- Mobile (375px base): same formula with mobile design width

**ALL sizes must use rem** — font-size, padding, margin, gap, width, height, border-radius, letter-spacing. Never use px directly except for `1px` borders.

## 2. Typography Utility Classes

Generate reusable typography classes in `@layer components` inside the page CSS file.

**Naming pattern:** `{platform}-{role}-{figmaPx}-{weight}`
- Platform: `pc` (desktop ≥640px), `sp` (mobile <640px)
- Role: `h1`, `h2`, `h3`, `body`, `caption`, `label`, `btn`, `link`
- figmaPx: the original Figma pixel size (integer)
- Weight: `r` (regular/400), `m` (medium/500), `s` (semibold/600), `b` (bold/700), `eb` (extrabold/800)

**Example:**
```css
@layer components {
  .pc-h2-54-s {
    @apply text-[2.8125rem] font-semibold leading-[1.2] tracking-[-0.02813rem];
  }
  .pc-body-16-r {
    @apply text-[0.8333rem] font-normal leading-[1.5] tracking-normal;
  }
  .sp-h2-28-s {
    @apply text-[1.75rem] font-semibold leading-[1.2] tracking-[-0.0175rem];
  }
}
```

Always generate BOTH `pc-*` and `sp-*` variants for every text style found in the design.

## 3. CSS Architecture — Tailwind Classes in JSX

Apply Tailwind utility classes directly in JSX. No separate CSS file for component styles (only typography utility classes remain in the page CSS file).

Rules:
- Use Tailwind utility classes (including arbitrary values `[...]`) directly in JSX `className`
- Use `cn()` from `@/shared/utils/cn` for conditional/merged classes
- Typography utility classes (`pc-h1-64-eb`, `sp-body-16-r`, etc.) are defined in the page CSS file and used alongside Tailwind classes in JSX
- No inline `style={{ }}` — use Tailwind arbitrary values instead

**Example:**
```tsx
// hero-section/index.tsx
export const HeroSection: React.FC = () => (
  <section className="relative w-full overflow-hidden">
    <div className="relative z-10 flex flex-col pt-[7.7083rem] px-[5.2083rem] pb-[4.1667rem]">
      <h2 className="pc-h1-64-eb uppercase text-white">Title</h2>
      <p className="pc-body-16-r text-white/80 max-w-[33.125rem]">Description</p>
    </div>
  </section>
);
```

## 4. HTML — Semantic & Flat

- Use semantic elements: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`, `<figure>`, `<figcaption>`
- **Minimize nesting** — max 4-5 levels deep. If deeper, flatten or extract a component.
- Clickable → `<button>` or `<a>`. Never `<div onClick>`.
- Lists → `<ul>/<ol>` + `<li>`. Never `<div>` repeated.
- Only ONE `<h1>` per page. Sections use `<h2>`, sub-sections `<h3>`.

## 5. Naming Conventions

### Images/Assets
- Temporary/placeholder images prefix: `d-` (e.g., `d-hero-banner.webp`) — easy to find and replace later
- Production images: descriptive kebab-case (e.g., `hero-banner.webp`, `product-iphone-15.webp`)
- Icons: prefixed with `ic-` (e.g., `ic-arrow-right.svg`, `ic-close.svg`)
- Logos: prefixed with `logo-` (e.g., `logo-kingtech.svg`)

### Variables & Code
- **No Vietnamese** in variable names, class names, file names
- Variables: `camelCase` — `heroTitle`, `productPrice`, `isMenuOpen`
- Components: `PascalCase` — `HeroSection`, `ProductCard`
- Files/folders: `kebab-case` — `hero-section/`, `product-card/`
- CSS classes: Tailwind utilities directly in JSX — no custom CSS class names for components
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` — `MAX_PRODUCTS`, `API_BASE_URL`
- Correct English grammar — `productList` not `listProduct`, `isLoading` not `loadingIs`

## 6. SEO Requirements

Every page MUST include:

### Single H1
- Only ONE `<h1>` per page — typically the main heading in the hero section
- All other headings: `<h2>`, `<h3>`, etc. in proper hierarchy

### Metadata (in route page.tsx)
```tsx
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Page Title | Brand',
  description: 'Page description for search engines (120-160 chars)',
  keywords: ['keyword1', 'keyword2'],
  openGraph: {
    title: 'Page Title',
    description: 'Description',
    images: [{ url: '/og-image.jpg', width: 1200, height: 630 }],
  },
  alternates: {
    canonical: 'https://example.com/page',
    languages: { 'vi': '/vi/page', 'en': '/en/page' },
  },
  robots: { index: true, follow: true },
};
```

### JSON-LD Schema
```tsx
const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebPage', // or Organization, Product, Article, etc.
  name: 'Page Title',
  description: 'Description',
  // ... type-specific fields
};

// In the route component:
<script
  type="application/ld+json"
  dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}
/>
```

### hreflang (in layout or page)
For multi-language sites, add alternate language links via metadata.alternates.languages.

### robots.txt and sitemap
- `public/robots.txt` — allow crawling, reference sitemap
- `src/app/sitemap.ts` — dynamic sitemap generation
- `src/app/not-found.tsx` — custom 404 page

## 7. Asset Handling

- **NEVER** leave Figma MCP asset URLs in code (they expire in 7 days)
- Download images to `public/assets/images/[page-name]/`
- Download SVGs to `src/assets/icons/`
- Use WebP format for raster images when possible
- Optimize images: set explicit `width`/`height` or use Next.js `<Image>` component
- Lazy load below-fold images: `loading="lazy"`

## 8. Smart Component Decomposition

Target: **20-40 components** for a full landing page with 10-14 sections.

**Create a sub-component ONLY when:**
- Pattern repeats 3+ times (card grid, nav items)
- Section exceeds 300 lines
- Complex interactive state (carousel, accordion, dropdown)

**Keep inline:**
- Single text, button, icon, badge, simple container

## 9. Figma MCP Usage

Parse URL: `figma.com/design/{fileKey}/...?node-id={X-Y}` → `fileKey`, `nodeId: X:Y`

Required calls (in order):
1. `get_design_context({ fileKey, nodeId, framework: "react" })` — structure + code
2. `get_variable_defs({ fileKey, nodeId })` — design tokens
3. `get_code_connect_map({ fileKey, nodeId })` — existing component mappings
4. `get_screenshot({ fileKey, nodeIds: [nodeId] })` — visual reference
5. `get_image_fills({ fileKey, nodeId })` — downloadable assets

## 10. Font Acquisition (must match Figma)

Fonts must match the Figma design exactly. Try these sources in order:
1. **Google Fonts** via `next/font/google` — check if the font name exists
2. **@fontsource** npm package — `npm install @fontsource/{font-name}`
3. **Font files** — search `public/assets/fonts/` or download `.woff2` files
4. **Closest alternative** — if unavailable, find similar Google Font + add comment

Include ALL weights used in the design. Include `vietnamese` subset for Vietnamese content.

## 11. Quality Gates

Before marking any implementation complete:
1. ✅ `npm run dev` compiles without errors
2. ✅ `npx eslint . --fix` passes
3. ✅ `npx prettier --write .` formatted
4. ✅ No Figma asset URLs in code
5. ✅ No inline `style={{ }}` (use Tailwind classes)
6. ✅ No Vietnamese in variable/class names
7. ✅ Only one `<h1>` per page
8. ✅ JSON-LD schema present
9. ✅ Metadata complete

## 12. Visual Verification Loop (self-improving)

After build passes, verify section by section:
1. Screenshot each section in browser (Claude in Chrome MCP)
2. Screenshot same section in Figma (Figma MCP `get_screenshot`)
3. Compare with Claude Vision — check typography, spacing, colors, layout, assets
4. Fix ALL differences found
5. Re-screenshot and compare again
6. **Repeat until the section matches Figma** — do NOT stop after a fixed number of iterations
7. Move to next section only when current one is verified
8. Final full-page comparison after all sections pass

Only negligible differences are acceptable (subpixel rendering, anti-aliasing).
